Part I - Ford GoBike System Data¶

by Glory Temitayo Andrew¶

Introduction¶

This data set includes information about individual rides made in a bike-sharing system covering the greater San Francisco Bay area.

# Converting start_time and end_time into a datetime datatype
df['start_time'] = pd.to_datetime(df['start_time'])
df['end_time'] = pd.to_datetime(df['end_time'])

# Converting member_birth_year into an integer datatype
df['member_birth_year'] = df['member_birth_year'].astype('int')

# Converting start_station_id, end_station_id, and bike_id into a string datatype
df['start_station_id'] = df['start_station_id'].astype('str')
df['end_station_id'] = df['end_station_id'].astype('str')
df['bike_id'] = df['bike_id'].astype('str')

# Creats a subplot function that plots a variable against an integer 
def subPlot(x, y, xlab, ylab, title):
    
    plt.figure(figsize=(15,10))
    plt.subplot(2,1,2)
    plt.bar(x.index , y.values)
    plt.ylabel(ylab , size= 12)
    plt.xlabel(xlab , size= 12)
    plt.title(title)
    plt.xticks(rotation = 80)

df['start_hour'] = df['start_hour'].astype(hour_category)

plt.title("Trip distribution over hours of the day")

plt.ylabel('Count')

From the chart above, we see that the hours of 8-9am and 5-6pm have the highest number of trips, which may implies the period at which workers, student and artisan goes to work/school and come back home.

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

  1. The majority of riders are subscribers between the ages of 20 and 60.
  2. Trips are more frequent during the weekdays with more rides during opening and closing working hours than on weekendsimplying that the majority of bike users are working-class, students and residents who use bikes to commute to work/school.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

  1. Member's age was calculated by subtracting the birthyear from the current year. This was done to provide a more comprehensive picture of the analysis.
  2. Trip duration was converted from seconds to minutes for a less complicated view.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in the dataset?¶

Trip duration is highly dependent on the member's age and user type. Furthermore, the start and end stations have little influence on the trip duration. It just implies that certain starting stations have longer trip duration as starting points and some end stations have longer trip duration as ending points.

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features (not the main feature(s) of interest)?¶

The interesting relationships between other features for me is the fact that female gender travels longer distance than male gender. I never expected that.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest?¶

No

Conclusion¶

This analysis establishes the factthat those who use bikes as a mode of transportation do so more on weekdays than on weekends, with peak hours being when they ride to and from work/school.

It's worth noting that the duration of trips during the week is much less than on weekends for both user types

Younger people tends to travel shorter distance than older ones
